== Usage == <!--T:8-->

=== Tool with pre-selection === <!--T:9-->

<!--T:10-->
# Select one or more faces or objects in the 3D View or the Tree View. Multiple faces across different objects are allowed; the tool will create one Covering per selected item in a single batch operation.
# There are several ways to invoke the tool:
#* Press the {{Button|[[Image:BIM_Covering.svg|16px]] [[BIM_Covering|Covering]]}} button.
#* Select the {{MenuCommand|3D/BIM → [[Image:BIM_Covering.svg|16px]] Covering}} option from the menu.
#* Use the keyboard shortcut: {{KEY|C}} then {{KEY|V}}.
# The task panel opens with the selection already populated. Adjust parameters and press {{Button|OK}}.

=== Tool without pre-selection === <!--T:11-->

<!--T:12-->
# Make sure nothing is selected.
# Invoke the tool as described above.
# The task panel opens with the {{Button|Pick}} button active (indicated by the red recording icon and the label ''Picking…''). The 3D View is in selection mode.
# Click a face or object to select it as the base:
#* Objects can be selected from the Tree View by a single click.
#* To select a specific face from the 3D View, click the object once to select it, then click the face a second time. Clicking an edge on the first or second click will clear the selection rather than adding to it.
#* Hold {{KEY|Ctrl}} while clicking to accumulate multiple items before confirming.
# Adjust parameters and press {{Button|OK}} to create the Covering(s).

<!--T:13-->
* '''Entering Continue mode:''' Check the '''Continue''' mode checkbox (at the bottom of the Geometry panel) to keep the task panel open after each OK, resetting for the next covering. This is useful for applying the same finish settings to many faces one at a time.
* '''Exiting Continue mode:''' To stop creating coverings while Continue mode is active, press {{Button|Cancel}} instead of {{Button|OK}}. The last covering already created is not affected. Alternatively, uncheck the '''Continue''' checkbox before pressing {{Button|OK}} to commit the current covering and close the panel normally.

=== Edit mode === <!--T:14-->

<!--T:15-->
Double-click an existing Covering object in the Tree View to reopen the task panel in edit mode. All parameters can be changed. To reassign the base face, activate the {{Button|Pick}} button and select a new face.

=== Undo behavior === <!--T:16-->

<!--T:17-->
The undo behaviour differs between creation modes:

<!--T:18-->
* In single creation mode (no Continue), the entire operation — including the covering object and its base face assignment — is a single undo step.
* In batch creation mode (multiple pre-selected faces), all coverings created in the batch are grouped into a single undo step; undoing it removes all of them at once.
* In Continue mode, each individual OK is its own undo step, so coverings can be undone one at a time.
* In edit mode, the changes made during a session are committed as a single undo step when OK is pressed; pressing Cancel leaves the object unchanged and adds nothing to the undo history.

== Finish modes == <!--T:19-->

<!--T:20-->
The Finish mode controls how the covering geometry is generated and displayed. It can be changed at any time without losing other settings.

<!--T:21-->
All modes except '''Hatch Pattern''' support texture mapping via the [[#Visuals|Visuals]] task panel section.

=== Solid Tiles === <!--T:22-->

<!--T:23-->
Individual 3D tiles are generated with real joint gaps between them via boolean subtraction. Each tile is a separate solid extruded to the specified thickness. This mode is the most geometrically accurate and produces the most informative Quantity Take-Off data (including individual tile counts and waste). It is also the least performant. It is best suited for close-up renders, detailed drawings, and material schedules.

<!--T:24-->
'''Performance note:''' When the tile count exceeds 10,000 or the joint width is less than 0.1 mm, the engine automatically switches to analytical mode: the geometry falls back to a single monolithic solid, while tile counts and areas are still computed mathematically. A warning is printed to the Report View when this occurs. At counts above 100,000, layout lines are also hidden.

=== Parametric Pattern === <!--T:25-->

<!--T:26-->
A grid of tile layout lines is drawn on a single flat slab without extruding individual tiles. The slab thickness is controlled by the Tile Thickness parameter. This mode is lighter to display and recompute than Solid Tiles, making it suitable for large-scale views, preliminary layouts, or performance-sensitive models.

=== Monolithic === <!--T:27-->

<!--T:28-->
A single continuous surface is produced with no tile subdivisions. The tile dimensions define the texture repeat period only. This mode is intended for seamless or near-seamless materials such as plaster, paint, polished concrete, carpet, or linoleum, where individual unit boundaries are absent or irrelevant.

=== Hatch Pattern === <!--T:29-->

<!--T:30-->
A 2D CAD-style hatch pattern is applied to a single flat slab using a standard {{FileName|.PAT}} pattern file. This mode is intended for technical drawings and plans. A PAT file and pattern name must be specified; FreeCAD's bundled {{FileName|FCPAT.pat}} is offered as the default. Texture mapping is not available in this mode.

== Options == <!--T:31-->

<!--T:32-->
[[File:BIM Covering Task Panel.png|thumb|BIM Covering task panel]]

<!--T:33-->
The task panel is divided into three collapsible sections that logically group all controls.

=== Covering Definition === <!--T:34-->

<!--T:35-->
{| class="wikitable"
! Control
! Description
|-
| '''Base'''
| The face or object the covering is applied to. Click {{Button|Pick}} to change it interactively.
|-
| '''Mode'''
| Selects the geometry generation strategy (see [[#Finish_Modes|Finish Modes]] above).
|-
| '''Thickness'''
| Extrusion depth of each tile (or slab thickness in non-Solid modes).
|-
| '''Length'''
| Tile body length along the U axis.
|-
| '''Width'''
| Tile body width along the V axis.
|-
| '''Joint width'''
| Width of the gap between tiles.
|-
| '''Stagger'''
| Running bond offset: Stacked (None), 1/2, 1/3, 1/4, or Custom. The Custom option enables a free offset input.
|-
| '''Continue'''
| When checked, pressing OK creates the covering and immediately resets the panel for a new one, without closing the task panel.
|}

=== Layout and Boundaries === <!--T:36-->

<!--T:37-->
{| class="wikitable"
! Control
! Description
|-
| '''Alignment'''
| Preset or Custom grid anchor (see [[#Alignment|Alignment]] section below).
|-
| '''U offset'''
| Manual offset of the grid origin along the face U axis. Active only in Custom alignment mode. FreeCAD expressions are supported.
|-
| '''V offset'''
| Same as above, for V axis.
|-
| '''Rotation'''
| Rotates the entire tile grid around the face normal.
|-
| '''Border setback'''
| Shrinks the tiling area inward from the face boundary by the given distance. Useful to keep tiles away from skirting boards or other perimeter elements.
|}

=== Visuals === <!--T:38-->

<!--T:39-->
{| class="wikitable"
! Control
! Description
|-
| '''Texture image'''
| An image file mapped continuously onto the covering surface. The file is embedded in the document.
|-
| '''Texture scale'''
| Multiplier applied to the texture repeat in U and V independently. Values above 1.0 stretch the texture; values below 1.0 compress it.
|}

== Alignment == <!--T:40-->

<!--T:41-->
The ''Alignment'' setting controls where the tile grid is anchored relative to the base face boundary.

=== Preset alignments === <!--T:42-->

<!--T:43-->
Five presets are available: '''Center''', '''Top Left''', '''Top Right''', '''Bottom Left''', '''Bottom Right'''.

<!--T:44-->
For corner presets, the ''named corner of the lead tile'' is aligned to the ''named corner of the face''. For instance, '''Top Right''' places the top-right corner of the lead tile flush with the top-right corner of the face. The lead tile is a conceptual anchor, not a physical tile: it's the one used to define the alignment. For '''Center''', the center of the lead tile is placed at the center of the face.

<!--T:45-->
Corner names follow the face orientation: on a rotated surface, '''Top Right''' refers to the top-right corner of the face itself, not of the viewport or the world. Grout joints at the aligned corner extend outward beyond the face boundary. For the Center preset, the center of a single tile is placed at the face center.

=== Custom alignment === <!--T:46-->

<!--T:47-->
Selecting ''Custom'' activates the ''U offset'' and ''V offset'' input fields, which shift the grid origin by an arbitrary distance along the face coordinate axes. The offset is measured from the face center. FreeCAD parametric expressions are accepted in both fields, allowing the offset to be driven by a [[Std_VarSet|VarSet]], spreadsheet cell or a model dimension.

=== Interactive === <!--T:48-->

<!--T:49-->
The {{Button|Interactive}} button (available in Custom mode) enters an interactive grid placement mode. While active, a tile preview tracks the mouse cursor in the 3D View, anchored at its bottom-left corner.

<!--T:50-->
'''Setting the origin:''' click any point in the 3D View — typically a vertex of the base face — to set the grid origin at that point. The click ends the interactive session: the U offset, V offset and Rotation fields are updated automatically and the alignment is switched to Custom. To exit without placing, press {{KEY|Esc}}.

<!--T:51-->
'''Rotating the grid:''' optionally, before clicking to confirm the origin, press {{KEY|R}} to rotate the tile wireframe clockwise by one step, or {{KEY|Shift}}+{{KEY|R}} to rotate counter-clockwise. The Rotation field updates live with each keypress. The step size defaults to 15° and can be changed by setting {{PropertyView|Pick Rotation Step}} in the View tab of the object's properties panel.

<!--T:52-->
If a rotation has been entered manually in the Rotation field before activating {{Button|Interactive}}, the wireframe will start at that angle rather than zero. It is not possible to manually enter the rotation in the input field during interactive mode.

=== Match working plane === <!--T:53-->

<!--T:54-->
The {{Button|Match Working Plane}} button sets the grid origin to the projection of the current FreeCAD working plane origin onto the base face, expressed as a U/V offset. This allows the tile grid to be aligned to a known reference point in the model.

== Texture mapping == <!--T:55-->

<!--T:56-->
Texture images are mapped onto the covering surface using a continuous linear projection with a period equal to {{Incode|TileLength + JointWidth}} in U and {{Incode|TileWidth + JointWidth}} in V. The texture repeats seamlessly across the entire surface with no gaps.

== Quantity take-off == <!--T:57-->

<!--T:58-->
The following properties are computed automatically on every recompute and can be read from the object's Data panel or referenced in a FreeCAD spreadsheet:

<!--T:59-->
{| class="wikitable"
! Property
! Description
|-
| {{PropertyData|Count Full Tiles}}
| Number of tiles that fit entirely within the face boundary.
|-
| {{PropertyData|Count Partial Tiles}}
| Number of tiles that are cut by the boundary.
|-
| {{PropertyData|Hole Areas}}
| The individual area of each hole in the base face, in mm², sorted by size (largest first).
|-
| {{PropertyData|Net Area}}
| Surface area of the base face (the area to be covered).
|-
| {{PropertyData|Gross Area}}
| Total area of material consumed, including partial tiles ordered as full units.
|-
| {{PropertyData|Outer Area}}
| The area enclosed by the outer boundary of the base face, ignoring any holes.
|-
| {{PropertyData|Waste Area}}
| GrossArea − NetArea: the area of cut-off material that is discarded.
|-
| {{PropertyData|Total Joint Length}}
| Sum of all joint center-line lengths.
|-
| {{PropertyData|Perimeter Length}}
| Perimeter of the base face.
|}

=== Physical vs analytical calculation === <!--T:60-->

<!--T:61-->
When the tile count is within normal limits (up to 10,000 tiles) and the joint width is at least 0.1 mm, quantities are derived from the actual computed geometry (''physical mode''): tile counts are obtained by counting the resulting solids, and areas are measured from their faces. This is the most accurate method.

<!--T:62-->
When the tile count exceeds 10,000, or the joint is too narrow for stable boolean operations (< 0.1 mm), the engine switches to ''analytical mode'': the geometry falls back to a single monolithic solid, and counts and areas are computed mathematically from the tile dimensions and face area. The [[#Quantity_take-off|QTO values]] remain valid and usable in schedules; only the 3D representation is simplified.

<!--T:63-->
At counts above 100,000 (''extreme count'' mode), layout lines are additionally hidden to prevent display freezes.

<!--T:64-->
A status message is printed to the Report View whenever the engine falls back from physical to analytical mode.

=== Using QTO data in a spreadsheet === <!--T:65-->

<!--T:66-->
To reference a Covering's quantities in a FreeCAD spreadsheet, use the standard expression syntax. For example, to read the net area of a covering named {{Incode|Covering}}:

<!--T:67-->
{{Code|code=
=Covering.NetArea
}}

== Known limitations == <!--T:68-->

<!--T:69-->
# Because Coin3D (FreeCAD's 3D renderer) does not support discontinuous texture mapping, it is not possible to leave the joint region genuinely empty in the texture. As a workaround, the texture origin is shifted by half the joint width, so the tile body is centered within its period and the texture image is centered on the physical tile. Since the joint region cuts off only the outermost border of the texture on each side, this is visually indistinguishable from a true gap for typical joint widths (5–10 mm with 300 mm tiles). For cases where the joint is large relative to the tile — and the cut-off edge is noticeable — the joint appearance can be incorporated directly into the texture image itself, for example by including a grout-coloured border.
# Texture images will not be present in Covering objects exported in IFC format. This is a limitation of the exporter, not of the Covering object. It is also unclear how well supported this feature is in most IFC viewers.
# At this time, and unlike other BIM objects, Additions and Subtractions support is not yet implemented.
# If both the Covering and its base object (e.g. Slab) are moved, the final position of the Covering will not be correct. If a relocation is desired, either the base or the Covering can be moved, but only one at a time. This is a limitation of all BIM objects, but on Covering objects it's easier to select both at the same time, since the base is deliberately not shown as the Covering's child on the Tree View.

== Properties == <!--T:70-->

=== Data === <!--T:71-->

<!--T:72-->
An Arch Covering object shares the common properties and behaviors of all [[Arch_Component|Arch Components]].

<!--T:73-->
{{TitleProperty|Boundaries}}

<!--T:74-->
* {{PropertyData|Border Setback|Length}}: Inward setback from the face perimeter.

<!--T:75-->
{{TitleProperty|Covering}}

<!--T:76-->
* {{PropertyData|Base|LinkSub}}: The face or object the covering is applied to.
* {{PropertyData|Finish Mode|Enumeration}}: Geometry generation strategy: Solid Tiles, Parametric Pattern, Monolithic, or Hatch Pattern.
* {{PropertyData|Rotation|Angle}}: Rotation of the tile grid around the face normal (degrees).
* {{PropertyData|Tile Alignment|Enumeration}}: Grid anchor preset or Custom.

<!--T:77-->
{{TitleProperty|IFC}}

<!--T:78-->
* {{PropertyData|Ifc Type|Enumeration}}: Fixed to "Covering" for IFC export.

<!--T:79-->
{{TitleProperty|IFC Attributes}}

<!--T:80-->
* {{PropertyData|Predefined Type|Enumeration}}: IFC subtype: FLOORING, CLADDING, ROOFING, MOLDING, SKIRTINGBOARD, CEILING, WRAPPING, or NOTDEFINED.

<!--T:81-->
{{TitleProperty|Pattern}}

<!--T:82-->
* {{PropertyData|Pattern File|FileIncluded}}: Embedded {{FileName|.PAT}} file for Hatch Pattern mode.
* {{PropertyData|Pattern Name|String}}: Name of the pattern within the PAT file.
* {{PropertyData|Pattern Scale|Float}}: Scale factor for the hatch pattern.

<!--T:83-->
{{TitleProperty|Quantities}}

<!--T:84-->
* {{PropertyData|Count Full Tiles|Integer}}: Number of uncut tiles.
* {{PropertyData|Count Partial Tiles|Integer}}: Number of cut tiles.
* {{PropertyData|Gross Area|Area}}: Total material area consumed.
* {{PropertyData|Hole Areas|FloatList}}: Sorted list of individual hole areas, largest first, in mm².
* {{PropertyData|Net Area|Area}}: Surface area of the base face.
* {{PropertyData|Outer Area|Area}}: Total covering area including hole areas.
* {{PropertyData|Outer Perimeter|Length}}: Base face perimeter length.
* {{PropertyData|Total Joint Length|Length}}: Total joint center-line length.
* {{PropertyData|Waste Area|Area}}: Cut-off material area (Gross Area − Net Area).

<!--T:85-->
{{TitleProperty|Tiles}}

<!--T:86-->
* {{PropertyData|Alignment Offset|Vector}}: Grid origin offset from face center (X=U, Y=V).
* {{PropertyData|Joint Width|Length}}: Width of the gap between tiles.
* {{PropertyData|Stagger Custom|Length}}: Custom running bond offset (active when ''Stagger Type'' is Custom).
* {{PropertyData|Stagger Type|Enumeration}}: Running bond type: Stacked, Half, Third, Quarter, or Custom.
* {{PropertyData|Tile Length|Length}}: Tile body length in the U direction.
* {{PropertyData|Tile Thickness|Length}}: Tile extrusion depth (or slab thickness).
* {{PropertyData|Tile Width|Length}}: Tile body width in the V direction.

<!--T:87-->
{{TitleProperty|Visual}}

<!--T:88-->
* {{PropertyData|Texture Image|FileIncluded}}: Embedded image file for texture mapping.
* {{PropertyData|Texture Scale|Vector}}: Texture repeat multiplier (X=U, Y=V).

=== View === <!--T:89-->

<!--T:90-->
Standard FreeCAD ViewProvider properties (Visibility, ShapeColor, Transparency, etc.) are inherited from the Arch Component base class.

<!--T:91-->
{{TitleProperty|Interactive}}

<!--T:92-->
* {{PropertyView|Pick Rotation Step|Angle}}: The rotation step applied to the tile grid per {{KEY|R}} / {{KEY|Shift}}+{{KEY|R}} keypress during interactive grid placement. Defaults to 15°. Can be set to any positive angle for finer or coarser control.

== Notes == <!--T:93-->

<!--T:94-->
* '''Corner alignment and joint bleed:''' For the Top Left, Top Right, and Bottom Right presets, the tile body corner sits flush with the face corner and the joint bleeds slightly outside the face boundary. This is intentional and physically correct — grout at a wall or floor edge is cut at the edge, not inset from it.

<!--T:95-->
* '''Edge clicks in the 3D View:''' When picking a base face interactively, clicking an edge instead of a face surface clears the current selection. If the selection field reverts to ''No selection'' unexpectedly, or if you are trying to select a base object with no faces (e.g. a Draft Rectangle), either select the object in the Tree View or double-click one of its edges on the 3D View to select the full object.

== Scripting == <!--T:96-->

<!--T:97-->
Covering objects can be created from Python using {{Incode|Arch.makeCovering()}}.

</translate>
{{Code|code=
import Arch

# Create a covering on a specific face of an object
box = FreeCAD.ActiveDocument.addObject("Part::Box", "Box")
FreeCAD.ActiveDocument.recompute()

covering = Arch.makeCovering((box, ["Face6"]))
covering.TileLength = 300.0   # mm
covering.TileWidth  = 300.0
covering.TileThickness = 10.0
covering.JointWidth = 5.0
covering.TileAlignment = "Center"
covering.FinishMode = "Solid Tiles"

FreeCAD.ActiveDocument.recompute()
}}
<translate>

<!--T:102-->
The {{Incode|makeCovering}} function accepts:
* A single object: {{Incode|Arch.makeCovering(obj)}} — applies to the most visible face.
* A {{Incode|(object, [face_name])}} tuple: {{Incode|Arch.makeCovering((obj, ["Face6"]))}} — applies to a specific face.
* {{Incode|None}}: creates an unbound covering to be configured later.


